Description: An ADF file describes the design of an array, e.g., what sequence is located at each position on an array and what the annotation of this sequence is. If the investigation uses arrays for which a description has been previously provided, such as a standard commercial array, cross-references to entries in a public repository (e.g., an Array Express accession number) can be included instead of explicit array descriptions.
Structure: An optional header section providing some top-level information about the array design. 2- Main section with one row per feature on the array describing what sequence is located at each position on an

Fields.Name: Column
Fields.Description: Column position for a spot on the array
Fields.Label: Column

Fields.Name: Term Source Name
Fields.Description: In the ADF table, for each cross-reference provided, e.g.Reporter Database Entry [uniprot], the cross-referenced resource's name needs to be entered here, so the resource can be looked up via the URL in Term Source File.
Fields.Label: Term Source Name

Fields.Name: Row
Fields.Description: Row position for a spot on the array
Fields.Label: Row

Fields.Name: Version
Fields.Description: Version (or revision) number of the array design.
Fields.Label: Version

Fields.Name: Block Column
Fields.Description: Block Column position for a spot on the array
Fields.Label: Block Column

Fields.Name: Block Row
Fields.Description: Block row position for a spot on the array
Fields.Label: Block Row

Fields.Name: Comment
Fields.Description: The Comment columns are included as a basic extensibility mechanism for local implementations, analogous to the use of NameValueTypes in MAGEv1. The name associated with the comment is included in square brackets in the column heading, and the value(s) entered in the body of the column.
Fields.Label: Comment[<NAME>]

Fields.Name: Array Design Name
Fields.Description: An informative title of the array design. Should include the name of the manufacturer (e.g. Agilent) or the lab which designed it, the species, version number, purpose of the array (e.g. genotyping), the number of probes/features (e.g 450k)
Fields.Label: Array Design Name

Fields.Name: Printing Protocol
Fields.Description: How the probes were printed on the array. Include URLs to stable online resources if possible. Especially important if you are submitting a custom array printed with non-propreitary methods.
Fields.Label: Printing Protocol

Fields.Name: Provider
Fields.Description: Name and contact email address of the array design's submitter.
Fields.Label: Provider

Fields.Name: Substrate Type
Fields.Description: The material/substrate of the microarray.
Fields.Label: Substrate Type

Fields.Name: Surface Type
Fields.Description: The chemical coating on the surface of the substrate see below. Probes are immobilised by the coating.
Fields.Label: Surface Type

Fields.Name: Technology Type
Fields.Description: Printing/synthesis technology used when creating the microarray.
Fields.Label: Technology Type

Fields.Name: Composite Element Name
Fields.Description: Composite Element unique name. In case of different reporters that are designed from two exons of a gene, you can indicate that the reporters belong to the same "composite element"""
Fields.Label: Composite Element Name

Fields.Name: Term Source File
Fields.Description: The URL where an external database resource mentioned in Term Source Name  is hosted.
Fields.Label: Term Source File

Fields.Name: Term Source Version
Fields.Description: The version of the external database resource mentioned in Term Source Name  is hosted.
Fields.Label: Term Source Version

Fields.Name: Reporter Database Entry
Fields.Description: Annotation for Reporter. Cross-reference accession in external database. You can enter multiple accessions from the same database by separating them with semicolons, e.g. AJ12345;BX45678
Fields.Label: Reporter Database Entry[<REFSRC>]

Fields.Name: Control Type
Fields.Description: Type of Control the reporter represents
Fields.Label: Control Type

Fields.Name: Reporter Group
Fields.Description: A Reporter Group
Fields.Label: Reporter Group[<NAME>]

Fields.Name: Reporter Name
Fields.Description: Unique probe or probset name
Fields.Label: Reporter Name

Fields.Name: Reporter Group[role]
Fields.Description: Defined role of the probe at this location. Can be experimental or control
Fields.Label: Reporter Group[role]

Fields.Name: Composite Element Database Entry
Fields.Description: Annotation for Composite Element. Cross-reference accession in external database. You can enter multiple accessions from the same database by separating them with semicolons, e.g. AJ12345;BX45678
Fields.Label: Composite Element Database Entry[<REFSRC>]

Fields.Name: Sequence Polymer Type
Fields.Description: The polymer that makes up the probes.
Fields.Label: Sequence Polymer Type

Description: A custom domain for collecting processed cytometry data, which is primarily about collecting observations about cells and populations of cells and their expression of certain markers
Structure: One record per measured prameter per cell population (group) per biospecimen identifier

Fields.Name: POP
Fields.Description: A description of the group / population that a number of cells have been classified into
Fields.Label: Name of population

Fields.Name: FEAT
Fields.Description: The molecular feature, biomarker that is being measured for this group of cells (e.g. CD14, TNFR1 ?)
Fields.Label: Feature

Fields.Name: COUNT
Fields.Description: The number of cells in each node
Fields.Label: The number of cells in each node

Fields.Name: DOMAIN
Fields.Description: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.
Fields.Label: Domain Abbreviation

Fields.Name: OBSMEA
Fields.Description: The measruement observed for each feature (e.g. Median Intensity, CVS ?)
Fields.Label: Observed measure

Fields.Name: PERTOT
Fields.Description: Percentage of cells in each population (group) as proportion of the total number of cells in each sample
Fields.Label: Percent of total

Fields.Name: OBSVALUE
Fields.Description: The Observed value for the measure specified in OBSMEA
Fields.Label: Observed Value

Fields.Name: SAMPLEID
Fields.Description: Unique identifier for a sample
Fields.Label: Sample Identifier

Description: A custom domain for collecting processed high dimensional assay data, which is primarily about collecting observations about samples and their expression of certain markers
Structure: One record per measured prameter per biospecimen identifier

Fields.Name: FEAT
Fields.Description: The molecular feature, biomarker that is being measured for this group of cells (e.g. CD14, TNFR1 ?)
Fields.Label: Feature

Fields.Name: DOMAIN
Fields.Description: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.
Fields.Label: Domain Abbreviation

Fields.Name: OBSMEA
Fields.Description: The measruement observed for each feature (e.g. Median Intensity, CVS ?)
Fields.Label: Observed Measure

Fields.Name: OBSVAL
Fields.Description: The Observed value for the measure specified in OBSMEA
Fields.Label: Observed Value

Fields.Name: OBSVALU
Fields.Description: The unit of observed measure value
Fields.Label: Value Unit

Fields.Name: SPECIMEN
Fields.Description: Unique identifier for a specimen
Fields.Label: Bio-specimen Identifier

Description: A simple template for a two dimensional data matrix used for array data or any other assay data that is represented in a matrix structure, where columns/rows are sample or feature identifiers and cells are single measurement values  (e.g. log intensity)
Structure: A two dimensional data matrix with a single measurement for each feature/sample combination

Fields.Name: X
Fields.Description: Identifiers for columns of the matrix
Fields.Label: Column Identifier

Fields.Name: Y
Fields.Description: Identifiers for rows of the matrix
Fields.Label: Row Identifier

Fields.Name: VALUE
Fields.Description: Measured observation value
Fields.Label: Measured Value

Description: A findings domain that contains the details regarding the characteristics of biospecimens and extracted samples (e.g., RNA, DNA) such as specimen volume, quantity of extracted sample, specimen condition and the integrity of the DNA or RNA samples.
Structure: One record per measurement per biospecimen identifier per subject

Fields.Name: BSDY
Fields.Description: Study day of specimen collection relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC.
Fields.Label: Study Day of Specimen Collection

Fields.Name: BSCAT
Fields.Description: Used to define a category of topic-variable values. Example: MEASUREMENT, QUALITY
Fields.Label: Category for Biospecimen Test

Fields.Name: BSDTC
Fields.Description: Date and time of specimen collection
Fields.Label: Date/Time of Specimen Collection

Fields.Name: BSNAM
Fields.Description: Name or identifier of the vendor (e.g., laboratory) that provided the test results.
Fields.Label: Vendor Name

Fields.Name: BSSEQ
Fields.Description: Sequence Number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.
Fields.Label: Sequence Number

Fields.Name: BSTPT
Fields.Description: Text description of time when a measurement or observation should be taken as defined in the protocol. This may be represented as an elapsed time relative to a fixed reference point, such as time of last dose. See BSTPTNUM and BSTPTREF.
Fields.Label: Planned Time Point Name

Fields.Name: BSXFN
Fields.Description: Filename for an external file
Fields.Label: External File

Fields.Name: VISIT
Fields.Description: 1. Protocol-defined description of clinical encounter.2. May be used in addition to VISITNUM and/or VISITDY.
Fields.Label: Visit Name

Fields.Name: BSBLFL
Fields.Description: Indicator used to identify a baseline value. The value should be "Y" or null.
Fields.Label: Baseline Flag

Fields.Name: BSELTM
Fields.Description: Elapsed time relative to a planned fixed reference (BSTPTREF). This variable is useful where there are repetitive measures. Not a clock time or a date time variable, but an interval, represented as ISO duration.
Fields.Label: Planned Elapsed Time from Time Point Ref

Fields.Name: BSSCAT
Fields.Description: Used to define a further categorization of BSCAT values.
Fields.Label: Subcategory for Biospecimen Test

Fields.Name: BSSPEC
Fields.Description: Defines the type of specimen used for a measurement. Examples: SERUM, PLASMA, URINE, SOFT TISSUE.
Fields.Label: Specimen Type

Fields.Name: BSSPID
Fields.Description: Sponsor-defined reference number. Perhaps pre-printed on the CRF as an sdtm-1-3:Classifier.ExpecedVariablelicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor's operational database.
Fields.Label: Sponsor-Defined Identifier

Fields.Name: BSSTAT
Fields.Description: Used to indicate that a test was not done, or was attempted but did not generate a result. Should be null or have a value of NOT DONE.
Fields.Label: Completion Status

Fields.Name: BSTEST
Fields.Description: Long name for BSTESTCD. Examples: Volume, RNA Integrity Number
Fields.Label: Biospecimen Test Name

Fields.Name: DOMAIN
Fields.Description: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.
Fields.Label: Domain Abbreviation

Fields.Name: BSGRPID
Fields.Description: Optional group identifier, used to link together a block of related records within a subject in a domain.
Fields.Label: Group ID

Fields.Name: BSORRES
Fields.Description: Result of the vital signs measurement as originally received or collected.
Fields.Label: Result or Finding in Original Units

Fields.Name: BSREFID
Fields.Description: Internal or external identifier such as lab specimen ID.
Fields.Label: Reference ID

Fields.Name: SPDEVID
Fields.Description: Sponsor-defined identifier for a device.
Fields.Label: Sponsor Device Identifier

Fields.Name: STUDYID
Fields.Description: Unique identifier for a study.
Fields.Label: Study Identifier

Fields.Name: USUBJID
Fields.Description: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.
Fields.Label: Unique Subject Identifier

Fields.Name: VISITDY
Fields.Description: Planned study day of the visit based upon RFSTDTC in Demographics.
Fields.Label: Planned Study Day of Visit

Fields.Name: BSANTREG
Fields.Description: Defines the specific anatomical or biological region of a tissue, organ specimen or the region from which the specimen is obtained, as defined in the protocol, such as a section or part of what is described in the BSSPEC variable. Examples: CORTEX, MEDULLA, MUCOSA.
Fields.Label: Anatomical Region of Specimen

Fields.Name: BSMETHOD
Fields.Description: Method of the test or examination. Examples: SPECTROPHOTOMETRY, ELECTROPHORESIS.
Fields.Label: Method of Test or Examination

Fields.Name: BSORRESU
Fields.Description: Unit for BSORRES. Examples: mg, mL
Fields.Label: Original Units

Fields.Name: BSREASND
Fields.Description: Reason not done. Used in conjunction with BSSTAT when value is NOT DONE.
Fields.Label: Reason Not Done

Fields.Name: BSRFTDTC
Fields.Description: Date/time for a fixed reference time point defined by PFTPTREF.
Fields.Label: Date/Time of Reference Time Point

Fields.Name: BSSPCCND
Fields.Description: Defines the condition of the specimen. Examples: HEMOLYZED, ICTERIC, LIPEMIC.
Fields.Label: Specimen Condition

Fields.Name: BSSTRESC
Fields.Description: Contains the result value for all findings, copied or derived from BSORRES in a standard format or standard units. BSSTRESC should store all results or findings in character format; if results are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in BSSTRESN
Fields.Label: Character Result/Finding in Std Format

Fields.Name: BSSTRESN
Fields.Description: Used for continuous or numeric results or findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from BSSTRESC. BSSTRESN should store all numeric test results or findings.
Fields.Label: Numeric Result/Finding in Standard Units

Fields.Name: BSSTRESU
Fields.Description: Standardized unit used for BSSTRESC and BSSTRESN.
Fields.Label: Standard Units

Fields.Name: BSTESTCD
Fields.Description: Short character value for BSTEST used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical format to a horizontal format. The short value can be up to 8 characters. Examples: VOLUME, RIN
Fields.Label: Biospecimen Test Short Name

Fields.Name: BSTPTNUM
Fields.Description: Numerical version of BSTPT to aid in sorting.
Fields.Label: Planned Time Point Number

Fields.Name: BSTPTREF
Fields.Description: Name of the fixed reference point referred to by BSELTM, BSTPTNUM, and BSTPT. Examples: PREVIOUS DOSE, PREVIOUS MEAL.
Fields.Label: Time Point Reference

Fields.Name: VISITNUM
Fields.Description: 1. Clinical encounter number.2. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.
Fields.Label: Visit Number

Description: Adverse events may be captured either as free text or a pre-specified list of terms.
Structure: One record per adverse event per subject

Fields.Name: AEACN
Fields.Description: Describes changes to the study treatment as a result of the event. AEACN is specifically for the relationship to study treatment. AEACNOTH is for actions unrelated to dose adjustments of study treatment. Examples of AEACN values include ICH E2B values: DRUG WITHDRAWN, DOSE REDUCED, DOSE INCREASED, DOSE NOT CHANGED, UNKNOWN or NOT APPLICABLE.
Fields.Label: Action Taken with Study Treatment

Fields.Name: AECAT
Fields.Description: Used to define a category of related records. Example: BLEEDING, NEUROPSYCHIATRIC.
Fields.Label: Category for Adverse Event

Fields.Name: AEDUR
Fields.Description: Collected duration and unit of an adverse event. Used only if collected on the CRF and not derived from start and end date/times. Example: P1DT2H (for 1 day, 2 hours).
Fields.Label: Duration of Adverse Event

Fields.Name: AEHLT
Fields.Description: Dictionary-derived text description of the High Level Term for the primary System Organ Class.
Fields.Label: High Level Term

Fields.Name: AELLT
Fields.Description: Dictionary-derived text description of the Lowest Level Term.
Fields.Label: Lowest Level Term

Fields.Name: AELOC
Fields.Description: Describes anatomical location relevant for the event (e.g., LEFT ARM for skin rash).
Fields.Label: Location of Event

Fields.Name: AEOUT
Fields.Description: Description of the outcome of an event.
Fields.Label: Outcome of Adverse Event

Fields.Name: AEREL
Fields.Description: Records the investigator's opinion as to the causality of the event to the treatment. ICH E2A and E2B examples include NOT RELATED, UNLIKELY RELATED, POSSIBLY RELATED, RELATED. Controlled Terminology may be defined in the future. Check with regulatory authority for population of this variable.
Fields.Label: Causality

Fields.Name: AESEQ
Fields.Description: Sequence Number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.
Fields.Label: Sequence Number

Fields.Name: AESER
Fields.Description: Is this a serious event?
Fields.Label: Serious Event

Fields.Name: AESEV
Fields.Description: The severity or intensity of the event. Examples: MILD, MODERATE, SEVERE.
Fields.Label: Severity/Intensity

Fields.Name: AESOC
Fields.Description: Dictionary-derived text description of the primary System Organ Class. Will be the same as AEBODSYS if the primary SOC was used for analysis.
Fields.Label: Primary System Organ Class

Fields.Name: AESOD
Fields.Description: Did the serious event occur with an overdose?
Fields.Label: Occurred with Overdose

Fields.Name: AEENDY
Fields.Description: Study day of end of event relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC.
Fields.Label: Study Day of End of Adverse Event

Fields.Name: AEENRF
Fields.Description: Describes the end of the event relative to the sponsor-defined reference period. The sponsor-defined reference period is a continuous period of time defined by a discrete starting point (RFSTDTC) and a discrete ending point (RFENDTC) of the trial.
Fields.Label: End Relative to Reference Period

Fields.Name: AEHLGT
Fields.Description: Dictionary-derived text description of the High Level Group Term for the primary System Organ Class.
Fields.Label: High Level Group Term

Fields.Name: AEPATT
Fields.Description: Used to indicate the pattern of the event over time. Examples: INTERMITTENT, CONTINUOUS, SINGLE EVENT.
Fields.Label: Pattern of Adverse Event

Fields.Name: AEPTCD
Fields.Description: Dictionary-derived code for the Preferred Term.
Fields.Label: Preferred Term Code

Fields.Name: AESCAN
Fields.Description: Was the serious event associated with the development of cancer?
Fields.Label: Involves Cancer

Fields.Name: AESCAT
Fields.Description: A further categorization of adverse event. Example: NEUROLOGIC.
Fields.Label: Subcategory for Adverse Event

Fields.Name: AESDTH
Fields.Description: Did the serious event result in death?
Fields.Label: Results in Death

Fields.Name: AESMIE
Fields.Description: Do additional categories for seriousness apply?
Fields.Label: Other Medically Important Serious Event

Fields.Name: AESPID
Fields.Description: Sponsor-defined identifier. It may be pre-printed on the CRF as an sdtm-1-3:Classifier.ExpecedVariablelicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor's operational database. Example: Line number on an Adverse Events page.
Fields.Label: Sponsor-Defined Identifier

Fields.Name: AESTDY
Fields.Description: Study day of start of adverse event relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC.
Fields.Label: Study Day of Start of Adverse Event

Fields.Name: AETERM
Fields.Description: Verbatim name of the event.
Fields.Label: Reported Term for the Adverse Event

Fields.Name: DOMAIN
Fields.Description: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.
Fields.Label: Domain Abbreviation

Fields.Name: AEDECOD
Fields.Description: Dictionary-derived text description of AETERM or AEMODIFY. Equivalent to the Preferred Term (PT in MedDRA). The sponsor is sdtm-1-3:Classifier.ExpecedVariableected to provide the dictionary name and version used to map the terms utilizing the define.xml external codelist attributes.
Fields.Label: Dictionary-Derived Term

Fields.Name: AEENTPT
Fields.Description: Description of date/time in ISO 8601 character format of the reference point referred to by AEENRTPT. Examples: "2003-12-25" or "VISIT 2".
Fields.Label: End Reference Time Point

Fields.Name: AEGRPID
Fields.Description: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain for a subject.
Fields.Label: Group ID

Fields.Name: AEHLTCD
Fields.Description: Dictionary-derived code for the High Level Term for the primary System Organ Class.
Fields.Label: High Level Term Code

Fields.Name: AELLTCD
Fields.Description: Dictionary-derived code for the Lowest Level Term.
Fields.Label: Lowest Level Term Code

Fields.Name: AEPRESP
Fields.Description: A value of "Y" indicates that this adverse event was pre-specified on the CRF. Values are null for spontaneously reported events (i.e., those collected as free-text verbatim terms).
Fields.Label: Pre-Specified Adverse Event

Fields.Name: AEREFID
Fields.Description: Internal or external identifier such as a serial number on an SAE reporting form.
Fields.Label: Reference ID

Fields.Name: AESCONG
Fields.Description: Was the serious event associated with congenital anomaly or birth defect?
Fields.Label: Congenital Anomaly or Birth Defect

Fields.Name: AESHOSP
Fields.Description: Did the serious event sdtm-1-3:Classifier.RequiredVariableuire or prolong hospitalization?
Fields.Label: sdtm-1-3:Classifier.RequiredVariableuires or Prolongs Hospitalization

Fields.Name: AESLIFE
Fields.Description: Was the serious event life threatening?
Fields.Label: Is Life Threatening

Fields.Name: AESOCCD
Fields.Description: Dictionary-derived code for the primary System Organ Class. Will be the same as AEBDSYCD if the primary SOC was used for analysis.
Fields.Label: Primary System Organ Class Code

Fields.Name: AETOXGR
Fields.Description: Toxicity grade according to a standard toxicity scale such as Common Terminology Criteria for Adverse Events v3.0 (CTCAE). Sponsor should specify name of the scale and version used in the metadata (see 6.2.1.1, Assumption 6c). If value is from a numeric scale, represent only the number (e.g., "2" and not "Grade 2").
Fields.Label: Standard Toxicity Grade

Fields.Name: STUDYID
Fields.Description: Unique identifier for a study.
Fields.Label: Study Identifier

Fields.Name: USUBJID
Fields.Description: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.
Fields.Label: Unique Subject Identifier

Fields.Name: AEACNOTH
Fields.Description: Describes other actions taken as a result of the event that are unrelated to dose adjustments of study treatment. Usually reported as free text. Example: "TREATMENT UNBLINDED. PRIMARY CARE PHYSICIAN NOTIFIED."
Fields.Label: Other Action Taken

Fields.Name: AEBDSYCD
Fields.Description: Dictionary derived. Code for the body system or organ class used by the sponsor. When using a multi-axial dictionary such as MedDRA, this should contain the SOC used for the sponsor's analyses and summary tables, which may not necessarily be the primary SOC.
Fields.Label: Body System or Organ Class Code

Fields.Name: AEBODSYS
Fields.Description: Dictionary derived. Body system or organ class used by the sponsor from the coding dictionary (e.g., MedDRA). When using a multi-axial dictionary such as MedDRA, this should contain the SOC used for the sponsor's analyses and summary tables which may not necessarily be the primary SOC.
Fields.Label: Body System or Organ Class

Fields.Name: AECONTRT
Fields.Description: Was another treatment given because of the occurrence of the event?
Fields.Label: Concomitant or Additional Trtmnt Given

Fields.Name: AEENRTPT
Fields.Description: Identifies the end of the event as being before or after the reference time point defined by variable AEENTPT.
Fields.Label: End Relative to Reference Time Point

Fields.Name: AEHLGTCD
Fields.Description: Dictionary-derived code for the High Level Group Term for the primary System Organ Class.
Fields.Label: High Level Group Term Code

Fields.Name: AEMODIFY
Fields.Description: If AETERM is modified to facilitate coding, then AEMODIFY will contain the modified text.
Fields.Label: Modified Reported Term

Fields.Name: AERELNST
Fields.Description: Records the investigator's opinion as to whether the event may have been due to a treatment other than study drug. May be reported as free text. Example: "MORE LIKELY RELATED TO ASPIRIN USE."
Fields.Label: Relationship to Non-Study Treatment

Fields.Name: AESDISAB
Fields.Description: Did the serious event result in persistent or significant disability/incapacity?
Fields.Label: Persist or Signif Disability/Incapacity

Fields.Name: CECAT
Fields.Description: Used to define a category of related records.

Fields.Name: CESEQ

Fields.Label: Sequence Number

Fields.Name: CESEV
Fields.Description: The severity or intensity of the event. Examples: MILD, MODERATE, SEVERE.
Fields.Label: Severity/Intensity

Fields.Name: CEENRF
Fields.Description: Describes the end of the event relative to the sponsor-defined reference period. The sponsor-defined reference period is a continuous period of time defined by a discrete starting point and a discrete ending point (represented by RFSTDTC and RFENDTC in Demographics).
Fields.Label: End Relative to Reference Period

Fields.Name: CESCAT
Fields.Description: A further categorization of the condition or event.
Fields.Label: Subcategory for Clinical Event

Fields.Name: CESPID
Fields.Description: Sponsor-defined reference number. Perhaps pre-printed on the CRF as an sdtm-1-3:Classifier.ExpecedVariablelicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor's operational database. Example: Line number on a CRF page.
Fields.Label: Sponsor-Defined Identifier

Fields.Name: CESTAT

Fields.Name: CESTRF

Fields.Label: Start Relative to Reference Period

Fields.Name: CETERM
Fields.Description: Term for the medical condition or event. Most likely pre-printed on CRF.

Fields.Name: DOMAIN
Fields.Description: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

Fields.Name: CEDECOD

Fields.Name: CEENTPT
Fields.Description: Description or date/time in ISO 8601 character format of the reference point referred to by CEENRTPT. Examples: "2003-12-25" or "VISIT 2".

Fields.Name: CEGRPID
Fields.Description: Used to tie together a block of related records for a subject within a domain.

Fields.Name: CEOCCUR
Fields.Description: Used when the occurrence of specific events is solicited to indicate whether or not a clinical event occurred. Values are null for spontaneously reported events.

Fields.Name: CEPRESP
Fields.Description: Used to indicate whether the Event in CETERM was pre-specified. Value is Y for pre-specified events, null for spontaneously reported events.

Fields.Name: CESTTPT

Fields.Name: CEREASND

Description: A subject domain utilized for the submission of information encompassing and representing data, vocabulary or records related to disposition. (NCI)
Structure: One record per disposition status or protocol milestone per subject

Fields.Name: DSCAT
Fields.Description: Used to define a category of related records. DSCAT is now an "sdtm-1-3:Classifier.ExpecedVariableected" variable. DSCAT was sdtm-1-3:Classifier.PermissibleVariableissible in SDTMIG 3.1.1 and earlier versions. The change from "sdtm-1-3:Classifier.PermissibleVariableissible" to "sdtm-1-3:Classifier.ExpecedVariableected" is based on the sdtm-1-3:Classifier.RequiredVariableuirement to distinguish protocol milestones and/or other events from disposition events. DSCAT may be null if there are only "disposition events"; however, it is recommended that DSCAT always be populated.
Fields.Label: Category for Disposition Event

Fields.Name: DSSEQ
Fields.Description: Sequence Number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.
Fields.Label: Sequence Number

Fields.Name: EPOCH
Fields.Description: EPOCH may be used when DSCAT = "DISPOSITION EVENT". Examples: SCREENING, TREATMENT PHASE, FOLLOW-UP.

For example, if ARMCD values for a seven-period crossover were constructed using two-character abbreviations for each treatment and separating hyphens, the length of ARMCD values would be 20.
Fields.Label: Planned Arm Code

Fields.Name: DMDTC
Fields.Description: Date/time of demographic data collection.
Fields.Label: Date/Time of Collection

Fields.Name: DTHFL
Fields.Description: Indicates the subject died. Should be Y or null. Should be populated even when the death date is unknown.
Fields.Label: Subject Death Flag

Fields.Name: INVID
Fields.Description: An identifier to describe the Investigator for the study. May be used in addition to SITEID. Not needed if SITEID is equivalent to INVID.
Fields.Label: Investigator Identifier

Fields.Name: ACTARM
Fields.Description: Description of actual Arm. When an Arm is not planned (not in Trial Arms), ACTARM will be "Unplanned Treatment". Randomized subjects who were not treated will be given a value of "Not Treated". Values should be "Screen Failure" for screen failures and "Not Assigned" for subjects not assigned to treatment. Restricted to values in Trial Arms in all other cases.
Fields.Label: Description of Actual Arm

Fields.Name: DOMAIN
Fields.Description: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.
Fields.Label: Domain Abbreviation

Fields.Name: DTHDTC
Fields.Description: Date/time of death for any subject who died, in ISO 8601 format. Should represent the date/time that is captured in the clinical-trial database.
Fields.Label: Date/Time of Death

Fields.Name: ETHNIC
Fields.Description: The ethnicity of the subject. Sponsors should refer to "Collection of Race and Ethnicity Data in Clinical Trials" (FDA, September 2005) for guidance regarding the collection of ethnicity (http://www.fda.gov/cder/guidance/5656fnl.htm).
Fields.Label: Ethnicity

Fields.Name: INVNAM
Fields.Description: Name of the investigator for a site.
Fields.Label: Investigator Name

Fields.Name: SITEID
Fields.Description: Unique identifier for a site within a study.
Fields.Label: Study Site Identifier

Fields.Name: SUBJID
Fields.Description: Subject identifier, which must be unique within the study. Often the ID of the subject as recorded on a CRF.
Fields.Label: Subject Identifier for the Study

Fields.Name: BRTHDTC
Fields.Description: Date/time of birth of the subject.
Fields.Label: Date/Time of Birth

Fields.Name: COUNTRY
Fields.Description: Country of the investigational site in which the subject participated in the trial.
Fields.Label: Country

Fields.Name: RFENDTC
Fields.Description: Reference End Date/time for the subject in ISO 8601 character format. Usually equivalent to the date/time when subject was determined to have ended the trial, and often equivalent to date/time of last sdtm-1-3:Classifier.ExpecedVariableosure to study treatment. sdtm-1-3:Classifier.RequiredVariableuired for all randomized subjects; null for screen failures or unassigned subjects.
Fields.Label: Subject Reference End Date/Time

Fields.Name: RFICDTC
Fields.Description: Date/time of informed consent in ISO 8601 character format. This will be the same as the date of informed consent in the Disposition domain, if that protocol milestone is documented. Would be null only in studies not collecting the date of informed consent.
Fields.Label: Date/Time of Informed Consent

Fields.Name: RFSTDTC
Fields.Description: Reference Start Date/time for the subject in ISO 8601 character format. Usually equivalent to date/time when subject was first sdtm-1-3:Classifier.ExpecedVariableosed to study treatment. sdtm-1-3:Classifier.RequiredVariableuired for all randomized subjects; will be null for all subjects who did not meet the milestone the date sdtm-1-3:Classifier.RequiredVariableuires, such as screen failures or unassigned subjects.
Fields.Label: Subject Reference Start Date/Time

Fields.Name: STUDYID
Fields.Description: Unique identifier for a study.
Fields.Label: Study Identifier

Fields.Name: USUBJID
Fields.Description: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product. This must be a unique number, and could be a compound identifier formed by concatenating STUDYID-SITEID-SUBJID.
Fields.Label: Unique Subject Identifier

Fields.Name: ACTARMCD
Fields.Description: Code of actual Arm. When an Arm is not planned (not in Trial Arms), ACTARMCD will be UNPLAN. Randomized subjects who were not treated will be given a value of NOTTRT. Values should be "SCRNFAIL" for screen failures and "NOTASSGN" for subjects not assigned to treatment. Restricted to values in Trial Arms in all other cases. ACTARMCD is limited to 20 characters and does not have special character restrictions. The maximum length of ACTARMCD is longer than for other short variables to accommodate the kind of values that are likely to be needed for crossover trials.
Fields.Label: Actual Arm Code

Fields.Name: RFPENDTC
Fields.Description: Date/time when subject ended participation or follow-up in a trial, as defined in the protocol, in ISO 8601 character format. Should correspond to the last known date of contact. Examples include completion date, withdrawal date, last follow-up, date recorded for lost to follow up, or death date.
Fields.Label: Date/Time of End of Participation

Fields.Name: RFXENDTC
Fields.Description: Last date of sdtm-1-3:Classifier.ExpecedVariableosure to any protocol-specified treatment or therapy, equal to the latest value of EXENDTC (or the latest value of EXSTDTC if EXENDTC was not collected or is missing).
Fields.Label: Date/Time of Last Study Treatment

Fields.Name: RFXSTDTC
Fields.Description: First date of sdtm-1-3:Classifier.ExpecedVariableosure to any protocol-specified treatment or therapy, equal to the earliest value of EXSTDTC.
Fields.Label: Date/Time of First Study Treatment

Description: The subject element table describes the actual order of elements followed by the subject, together with the start date/time and end date/time for each element.
Structure: One record per actual Element per subject

Fields.Name: ETCD
Fields.Description:
1. ETCD (the companion to ELEMENT) is limited to 8 characters and does not have special character restrictions. These values should be short for ease of use in programming, but it is not sdtm-1-3:Classifier.ExpecedVariableected that ETCD will need to serve as a variable name.
2. If an encountered Element differs from the planned Element to the point that it is considered a new Element, then use "UNPLAN" as the value for ETCD to represent this Element.
Fields.Label: Element Code

Fields.Name: EPOCH
Fields.Description: Epoch associated with the Element in the planned sequence of Elements for the ARM to which the subject was assigned.
Fields.Label: Epoch

Fields.Name: SESEQ
Fields.Description: Sequence Number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. Should be assigned to be consistent chronological order.
Fields.Label: Sequence Number

Fields.Name: DOMAIN
Fields.Description: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.
Fields.Label: Domain Abbreviation

Fields.Name: ELEMENT
Fields.Description: The name of the Element. If ETCD has a value of "UNPLAN" then ELEMENT should be Null.
Fields.Label: Description of Element

Fields.Name: SEENDTC
Fields.Description: End date/time for an Element for each subject.
Fields.Label: End Date/Time of Element

Fields.Name: SESTDTC
Fields.Description: Start date/time for an Element for each subject.
Fields.Label: Start Date/Time of Element

Fields.Name: SEUPDES
Fields.Description: Description of what happened to the subject during this unplanned Element. Used only if ETCD has the value of "UNPLAN".
Fields.Label: Description of Unplanned Element

Fields.Name: STUDYID
Fields.Description: Unique identifier for a study.
Fields.Label: Study Identifier

Fields.Name: TAETORD
Fields.Description: Number that gives the planned order of the Element within the subject's assigned ARM.
Fields.Label: Planned Order of Element within Arm

Fields.Name: USUBJID
Fields.Description: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.
Fields.Label: Unique Subject Identifier

Description: The subject visits table describes the actual start and end data/time for each visit of each individual subject.
Structure: One record per actual visit per subject

Fields.Name: VISIT
Fields.Description:
1. Protocol-defined description of clinical encounter.
2. May be used in addition to VISITNUM and/or VISITDY as a text description of the clinical encounter.
Fields.Label: Visit Name

Fields.Name: DOMAIN
Fields.Description: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.
Fields.Label: Domain Abbreviation

Fields.Name: SVENDY
Fields.Description: Study day of end of visit relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC.
Fields.Label: Study Day of End of Visit

Fields.Name: SVSTDY
Fields.Description: Study day of start of visit relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC.
Fields.Label: Study Day of Start of Visit

Fields.Name: STUDYID
Fields.Description: Unique identifier for a study.
Fields.Label: Study Identifier

Fields.Name: SVENDTC
Fields.Description: End date/time of a Visit.
Fields.Label: End Date/Time of Visit

Fields.Name: SVSTDTC
Fields.Description: Start date/time for a Visit.
Fields.Label: Start Date/Time of Visit

Fields.Name: SVUPDES
Fields.Description: Description of what happened to the subject during an unplanned visit.
Fields.Label: Description of Unplanned Visit

Fields.Name: USUBJID
Fields.Description: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.
Fields.Label: Unique Subject Identifier

Fields.Name: VISITDY
Fields.Description: Planned study day of the start of the visit based upon RFSTDTC in Demographics.
Fields.Label: Planned Study Day of Visit

Fields.Name: VISITNUM
Fields.Description:
1. Clinical encounter number. (Decimal numbering may be useful for inserting unplanned visits.)
2. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.
Fields.Label: Visit Number

Description: The trial arms table describes each planned arm in the trial. An arm is described as an ordered sequence of elements.
Structure: One record per planned Element per Arm

Fields.Name: ARM
Fields.Description: Name given to an Arm or treatment group.
Fields.Label: Description of Planned Arm

Fields.Name: ETCD
Fields.Description: ETCD (the companion to ELEMENT) is limited to 8 characters and does not have special character restrictions. These values should be short for ease of use in programming, but it is not sdtm-1-3:Classifier.ExpecedVariableected that ETCD will need to serve as a variable name.
Fields.Label: Element Code

Fields.Name: ARMCD
Fields.Description: ARMCD is limited to 20 characters and does not have special character restrictions. The maximum length of ARMCD is longer than that for other "short" variables to accommodate the kind of values that are likely to be needed for crossover trials. For example, if ARMCD values for a seven-period crossover were constructed using two-character abbreviations for each treatment and separating hyphens, the length of ARMCD values would be 20.
Fields.Label: Planned Arm Code

Fields.Name: EPOCH
Fields.Description: Name of the Trial Epoch with which this Element of the Arm is associated.
Fields.Label: Epoch

Fields.Name: DOMAIN
Fields.Description: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.
Fields.Label: Domain Abbreviation

Fields.Name: ELEMENT
Fields.Description: The name of the Element. The same Element may occur more than once within an Arm.
Fields.Label: Description of Element

Fields.Name: STUDYID
Fields.Description: Unique identifier for a study.
Fields.Label: Study Identifier

Fields.Name: TAETORD
Fields.Description: Number that gives the order of the Element within the Arm.
Fields.Label: Order of Element within Arm

Fields.Name: TATRANS
Fields.Description: If the trial design allows a subject to transition to an Element other than the next Element in sequence, then the conditions for transitioning to those other Elements, and the alternative Element sequences, are specified in this rule (e.g., Responders go to washout).
Fields.Label: Transition Rule

Fields.Name: TABRANCH
Fields.Description: Condition subject met, at a "branch" in the trial design at the end of this Element, to be included in this Arm; (e.g., randomization to DRUG X).
Fields.Label: Branch

Description: The Trial Elements (TE) dataset contains the definitions of the elements that appear in the Trial Arms (TA) dataset. An Element may appear multiple times in the Trial Arms table because it appears either 1) in multiple Arms, 2) multiple times within an Arm, or 3) both. However, an Element will appear only once in the Trial Elements table.
Structure: One record per planned Element

Fields.Name: ETCD
Fields.Description: ETCD (the companion to ELEMENT) is limited to 8 characters and does not have special character restrictions. These values should be short for ease of use in programming, but it is not sdtm-1-3:Classifier.ExpecedVariableected that ETCD will need to serve as a variable name.
Fields.Label: Element Code

Fields.Name: TEDUR
Fields.Description: Planned Duration of Element in ISO 8601 format. Used when the rule for ending the Element is applied after a fixed duration.
Fields.Label: Planned Duration of Element

Fields.Name: DOMAIN
Fields.Description: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.
Fields.Label: Domain Abbreviation

Fields.Name: TEENRL
Fields.Description: sdtm-1-3:Classifier.ExpecedVariableresses rule for ending Element. Either TEENRL or TEDUR must be present for each Element.
Fields.Label: Rule for End of Element

Fields.Name: TESTRL
Fields.Description: sdtm-1-3:Classifier.ExpecedVariableresses rule for beginning Element.
Fields.Label: Rule for Start of Element

Fields.Name: ELEMENT
Fields.Description: The name of the Element.
Fields.Label: Description of Element

Fields.Name: STUDYID
Fields.Description: Unique identifier for a study.
Fields.Label: Study Identifier

Description: The Trial Inclusion Exclusion (TI) dataset is not subject oriented. It contains all the inclusion and exclusion criteria for the trial, and thus provides information that may not be present in the subject-level data on inclusion and exclusion criteria.
Structure: One record per I/E criterion

Fields.Name: TIRL
Fields.Description: Rule that sdtm-1-3:Classifier.ExpecedVariableresses the criterion in computer-executable form (see assumption 4 below).
Fields.Label: Inclusion/Exclusion Criterion Rule

Fields.Name: IECAT
Fields.Description: Used for categorization of the inclusion or exclusion criteria.
Fields.Label: Inclusion/Exclusion Category

Fields.Name: DOMAIN
Fields.Description: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.
Fields.Label: Domain Abbreviation

Fields.Name: IESCAT
Fields.Description: A further categorization of the exception criterion. Can be used to distinguish criteria for a sub-study or for to categorize as a major or minor exceptions. Examples: MAJOR, MINOR.
Fields.Label: Inclusion/Exclusion Subcategory

Fields.Name: IETEST
Fields.Description: Full text of the inclusion or exclusion criterion. The prefix "IE" is used to ensure consistency with the IE domain.
Fields.Label: Inclusion/Exclusion Criterion

Fields.Name: TIVERS
Fields.Description: The number of this version of the Inclusion/Exclusion criteria. May be omitted if there is only one version.
Fields.Label: Protocol Criteria Versions

Fields.Name: STUDYID
Fields.Description: Unique identifier for a study.
Fields.Label: Study Identifier

Fields.Name: IETESTCD
Fields.Description: Short name IETEST. It can be used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical to a horizontal format. The value in IETESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g., "1TEST"). IETESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. The prefix "IE" is used to ensure consistency with the IE domain.
Fields.Label: Incl/Excl Criterion Short Name

Description: The Trial Summary (TS) dataset allows the sponsor to submit a summary of the trial in a structured format. Each record in the Trial Summary dataset contains the value of a parameter, a characteristic of the trial. For example, Trial Summary is used to record basic information about the study such as trial phase, protocol title, and trial objectives. The Trial Summary dataset contains information about the planned and actual trial characteristics.
Structure: One record per trial summary parameter value

Fields.Name: TSSEQ
Fields.Description: Sequence number given to ensure uniqueness within a dataset.  Allows inclusion of multiple records for the same TSPARMCD, and can be used to join related records.
Fields.Label: Sequence Number

Fields.Name: TSVAL
Fields.Description: Value of TSPARM. Example: "ASTHMA" when TSPARM value is "Trial Indication". TSVAL can only be null when TSVALNF is populated. Text over 200 characters can be added to additional columns TSVAL1-TSVALn.
Fields.Label: Parameter Value

Fields.Name: DOMAIN
Fields.Description: Two-character abbreviation for the domain, which must be TS.
Fields.Label: Domain Abbreviation

Fields.Name: TSPARM
Fields.Description: Term for the Trial Summary Parameter. The value in TSPARM cannot be longer than 40 characters. Examples Planned Minimum Age of Subjects, Planned Maximum Age of Subjects.
Fields.Label: Trial Summary Parameter

Fields.Name: STUDYID
Fields.Description: Unique identifier for a study.
Fields.Label: Study Identifier

Fields.Name: TSGRPID
Fields.Description: Used to tie together a group of related records.
Fields.Label: Group ID

Fields.Name: TSVALCD
Fields.Description: This is the code of the term in TSVAL. For example; 6CW7F3G59X is the code for Gabapentin, C49488 is the code for Y. The length of this variable can be longer than 8 to accommodate the length of the external terminology.
Fields.Label: Parameter Value Code

Fields.Name: TSVALNF
Fields.Description: Null flavor for the value of TSPARM, to be populated if and only if TSVAL is null.
Fields.Label: Parameter Null Flavor

Fields.Name: TSPARMCD
Fields.Description: TSPARMCD (the companion to TSPARM) is limited to 8 characters and does not have special character restrictions. These values should be short for ease of use in programming, but it is not sdtm-1-3:Classifier.ExpecedVariableected that TSPARMCD will need to serve as variable names. Examples: AGEMIN, AGEMAX.
Fields.Label: Trial Summary Parameter Short Name

Fields.Name: TSVCDREF
Fields.Description: The name of the Reference Terminology from which TSVALCD is taken. For example; CDISC, SNOMED, ISO 8601.
Fields.Label: Name of the Reference Terminology

Fields.Name: TSVCDVER
Fields.Description: The version number of the Reference Terminology, if applicable.
Fields.Label: Version of the Reference Terminology

Description: The Trial Visits (TV) dataset describes the planned Visits in a trial. Visits are defined as "clinical encounters" and are described using the timing variables VISIT, VISITNUM, and VISITDY. Protocols define Visits in order to describe assessments and procedures that are to be performed at the Visits.
Structure: One record per planned Visit per Arm

Fields.Name: ARM
Fields.Description:
1. Name given to an Arm or Treatment Group.
2. If the timing of Visits for a trial does not depend on which Arm a subject is in, then Arm should be left blank.
Fields.Label: Description of Planned Arm

Fields.Name: ARMCD
Fields.Description:
1.ARMCD is limited to 20 characters and does not have special character restrictions. The maximum length of ARMCD is longer than for other "short" variables to accommodate the kind of values that are likely to be needed for crossover trials. For example, if ARMCD values for a seven-period crossover were constructed using two-character abbreviations for each treatment and separating hyphens, the length of ARMCD values would be 20.
2. If the timing of Visits for a trial does not depend on which ARM a subject is in, then ARMCD should be null.
Fields.Label: Planned Arm Code

Fields.Name: VISIT
Fields.Description:
1. Protocol-defined description of clinical encounter.
2. May be used in addition to VISITNUM and/or VISITDY as a text description of the clinical encounter.
Fields.Label: Visit Name

Fields.Name: DOMAIN
Fields.Description: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.
Fields.Label: Domain Abbreviation

Fields.Name: TVENRL
Fields.Description: Rule describing when the Visit ends, in relation to the sequence of Elements.
Fields.Label: Visit End Rule

Fields.Name: TVSTRL
Fields.Description: Rule describing when the Visit starts, in relation to the sequence of Elements.
Fields.Label: Visit Start Rule

Fields.Name: STUDYID
Fields.Description: Unique identifier for a study.
Fields.Label: Study Identifier

Fields.Name: VISITDY
Fields.Description:
1. Planned study day of VISIT.
2. Due to its sequential nature, used for sorting.
Fields.Label: Planned Study Day of Visit

Fields.Name: VISITNUM
Fields.Description:
1. Clinical encounter number.
2. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.
Fields.Label: Visit Number
